SIMPLE: suite
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suite
<hw>Suite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Suit</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A retinue or company of
attendants, as of a distinguished personage; <as>as, the <ex>suite</ex>
of an ambassador</as>. See <er>Suit</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A connected series or succession of objects; a
number of things used or clessed together; a set; <as>as, a
<ex>suite</ex> of rooms; a <ex>suite</ex> of minerals</as>. See
<er>Suit</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 6.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mr. Barnard took one of the candles that stood upon the king's
table, and lighted his majesty through a <qex>suite</qex> of rooms till
they came to a private door into the library.</q>
<rj><qau>Boswell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>One of the old musical forms,
before the time of the more compact <xex>sonata</xex>, consisting of a
string or series of pieces all in the same key, mostly in various dance
rhythms, with sometimes an elaborate prelude. Some composers of the
present day affect the <xex>suite</xex> form.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suiting</ent>⟦br⟧
